President Obama has proclaimed October 2013 as National Cybersecurity Awareness Month in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of protecting our digital infrastructure from cyber threats and highlights the need for public awareness about cybersecurity. The President's administration is dedicated to building a system of protections in both the private and public sectors to keep out malicious forces while preserving the openness and power of the Internet. The proclamation also encourages individuals to understand the risks associated with being online and to take steps to secure personal information. The Department of Homeland Security's "Stop.Think.Connect." campaign is mentioned as a resource for empowering digital citizens with tools to make smart decisions in cyberspace. The proclamation concludes by calling upon the people of the United States to recognize the importance of cybersecurity and to observe the month with activities, events, and training that enhance national security and resilience.